WEBVTT

00:00:00.080 --> 00:00:02.277
I'm Dr. Daniel Kim, Founder and CEO of

00:00:02.278 --> 00:00:04.290
Sweetwater Digital Asset Consulting.

00:00:04.637 --> 00:00:05.656
This talk is called

00:00:05.657 --> 00:00:08.399
"Sound Money, Safe Mode" and it is a

00:00:08.400 --> 00:00:10.168
broad, big picture introduction

00:00:10.169 --> 00:00:12.193
to cryptocurrency and Monero.

00:00:12.559 --> 00:00:15.220
A little bit about myself -- so, academically,

00:00:15.221 --> 00:00:16.836
I'm trained as a particle physicist --

00:00:16.847 --> 00:00:19.015
I did my undergraduate and graduate work

00:00:19.026 --> 00:00:21.349
in experimental particle physics at Harvard.

00:00:21.359 --> 00:00:23.495
There, I had a habit ingrained in me

00:00:23.506 --> 00:00:24.710
to always look at data,

00:00:24.720 --> 00:00:26.373
so there's going to be a lot of data

00:00:26.374 --> 00:00:27.433
shown in this talk.

00:00:27.717 --> 00:00:28.708
Most of my career was

00:00:28.709 --> 00:00:30.421
spent in the non-profit sector.

00:00:30.422 --> 00:00:32.262
My first job out of grad school was with a

00:00:32.263 --> 00:00:34.229
symphony orchestra, where I ended up doing about

00:00:34.239 --> 00:00:35.875
700 concerts professionally --

00:00:35.886 --> 00:00:38.402
first as a violinist, and then later as a keyboardist.

00:00:38.836 --> 00:00:39.851
Concurrently with that,

00:00:39.862 --> 00:00:41.420
I jumped through the hoops to become

00:00:41.421 --> 00:00:43.560
board certified in radiation oncology physics.

00:00:43.663 --> 00:00:45.590
Then as a medical school professor in

00:00:45.600 --> 00:00:47.046
medical physics, I helped about a

00:00:47.047 --> 00:00:48.950
couple thousand patients with their

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:51.146
fights against cancer, by helping with

00:00:51.147 --> 00:00:53.063
the technical aspects of delivering

00:00:53.074 --> 00:00:54.578
high intensity radiation.

00:00:54.803 --> 00:00:56.801
It was as a med-school professor that I

00:00:56.812 --> 00:00:58.752
did my perhaps most "DEF CON" thing,

00:00:58.753 --> 00:01:00.869
which was to invent a device

00:01:00.879 --> 00:01:02.470
that did packet sniffing

00:01:02.480 --> 00:01:05.030
on a medical network to reconstruct

00:01:05.040 --> 00:01:07.350
treatment data being delivered to cancer

00:01:07.360 --> 00:01:09.841
patients just before the time of treatment.

00:01:10.144 --> 00:01:11.830
I signed up for the Executive MBA

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:13.830
program at Yale because I thought that

00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:16.679
I wanted to show an interest in the way

00:01:16.680 --> 00:01:17.670
that the world works

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:19.749
in a different way than in physics.

00:01:19.916 --> 00:01:21.270
Of course in physics, you're getting at how

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:23.068
the world works at the smallest levels

00:01:23.199 --> 00:01:25.396
but then to think broadly about "real world"

00:01:25.397 --> 00:01:27.429
human problems from a variety of

00:01:27.439 --> 00:01:29.590
perspectives, the MBA is good for that.

00:01:29.718 --> 00:01:31.749
While doing that, I made a switch to the

00:01:31.759 --> 00:01:32.796
for-profit sector --

00:01:32.807 --> 00:01:35.030
I joined a small hedge fund and I became

00:01:35.040 --> 00:01:36.469
Director of Research there.

00:01:36.479 --> 00:01:38.789
I was a co-author of a paper that won

00:01:38.799 --> 00:01:40.789
the top research award of the

00:01:40.799 --> 00:01:43.590
CFA Institute.  That paper was about the

00:01:43.600 --> 00:01:46.069
effect of liquidity on asset prices.

00:01:46.079 --> 00:01:47.910
In my spare time, I was getting more and

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:49.830
more interested into cryptocurrency and

00:01:49.840 --> 00:01:51.429
then I made a decision that

00:01:51.439 --> 00:01:53.056
this was a genuine innovation,

00:01:53.057 --> 00:01:54.652
of which there are not that many that happen

00:01:54.653 --> 00:01:56.230
in one's lifetime, so I

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:58.389
jumped to my own small business, which is

00:01:58.399 --> 00:02:00.870
what I do now as an independent consultant.

00:02:00.880 --> 00:02:03.630
Now I help bridge two very separate worlds

00:02:03.631 --> 00:02:05.286
as the founder and CEO of

00:02:05.287 --> 00:02:07.332
Sweetwater Digital Asset Consulting --

00:02:07.333 --> 00:02:09.378
there's the world that DEF CON

00:02:09.379 --> 00:02:10.469
represents, which is a

00:02:10.479 --> 00:02:12.209
non-commercial, open source,

00:02:12.220 --> 00:02:13.750
cypherpunk, grassroots,

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:15.703
cryptocurrency culture --

00:02:15.714 --> 00:02:17.909
and on the right side is the very

00:02:17.920 --> 00:02:19.610
parallel universe of

00:02:19.621 --> 00:02:21.350
traditional asset protection,

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:23.610
trust and family office portfolio management,

00:02:23.621 --> 00:02:25.110
estate and tax planning.

00:02:25.120 --> 00:02:27.249
These two separate worlds know

00:02:27.250 --> 00:02:29.183
very little about each other, in practice --

00:02:29.184 --> 00:02:30.835
they often make assumptions about

00:02:30.836 --> 00:02:33.030
each other that are based in fear --

00:02:33.040 --> 00:02:35.430
and so as one who has significant

00:02:35.440 --> 00:02:37.670
experience on both sides of this divide,

00:02:37.680 --> 00:02:40.229
I talk with "OG" crypto guys who want

00:02:40.239 --> 00:02:41.910
guidance in putting together a plan

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:44.150
to shield their crypto from future

00:02:44.160 --> 00:02:45.589
creditors, whether they be

00:02:45.599 --> 00:02:48.150
random people who might sue them or a

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:51.408
potentially vindictive future ex-spouse --

00:02:51.788 --> 00:02:53.247
and then from the other direction,

00:02:53.258 --> 00:02:56.016
I talk with traditional portfolio managers

00:02:56.017 --> 00:02:58.288
in the trust and estate world who are

00:02:58.289 --> 00:03:00.607
well acquainted with traditional assets,

00:03:00.608 --> 00:03:02.186
have heard about this "cryptocurrency stuff,"

00:03:02.187 --> 00:03:03.439
want to know if it's for real,

00:03:03.440 --> 00:03:05.670
and want to get in touch with a Sherpa

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:08.650
who can help them sort through all the noise.

00:03:09.030 --> 00:03:11.067
In my non-profit efforts these days

00:03:11.078 --> 00:03:12.735
I am also a community volunteer

00:03:12.746 --> 00:03:14.149
for the Monero project.

00:03:14.159 --> 00:03:17.398
My talking here is on a voluntary basis.

00:03:17.399 --> 00:03:19.494
I'm doing this because I personally feel that

00:03:19.505 --> 00:03:21.545
this is an important project for humanity.

00:03:21.546 --> 00:03:23.589
I think it's important for people to

00:03:23.599 --> 00:03:25.750
speak out and make their voices heard

00:03:25.761 --> 00:03:27.268
on matters like this.

00:03:27.279 --> 00:03:28.626
I do not receive any

00:03:28.637 --> 00:03:30.147
support from the Monero project,

00:03:30.158 --> 00:03:31.291
I've never asked for support

