00:05:01.089 --> 00:05:02.789
Here in this plot I'm showing U.S.

00:05:02.790 --> 00:05:04.950
government data all the way back to 1980,

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:07.308
so we're looking at 40 years of history here.

00:05:07.309 --> 00:05:09.517
The blue line is "U6" unemployment --

00:05:09.518 --> 00:05:11.036
this is the fraction of people

00:05:11.037 --> 00:05:12.310
who are either

00:05:12.320 --> 00:05:13.590
looking for work, or

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:15.189
working part-time when they want to be

00:05:15.199 --> 00:05:17.749
working full-time, or are so discouraged

00:05:17.759 --> 00:05:19.830
with their state of trying to find a job

00:05:19.840 --> 00:05:20.870
that they've given up.

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:22.994
This is contrasting with "U3,"

00:05:22.995 --> 00:05:25.422
which is only counting those people who are

00:05:25.423 --> 00:05:27.848
actively looking for work and can't find it.

00:05:27.849 --> 00:05:29.523
So U6 is a broader measure and so

00:05:29.524 --> 00:05:31.758
it's widely considered to be more accurate.

00:05:31.759 --> 00:05:33.849
Unemployment in the year 2020

00:05:33.850 --> 00:05:35.670
spiked up to the highest level

00:05:35.680 --> 00:05:37.577
ever in recorded history -- at least

00:05:37.578 --> 00:05:39.830
of the U6 unemployment rate --

00:05:39.831 --> 00:05:41.887
it spiked up to about 23 percent.

00:05:41.888 --> 00:05:43.392
Fortunately that's gone down a bit

00:05:43.393 --> 00:05:44.710
since then, but it's still

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:46.576
definitely not a pretty number.

00:05:46.577 --> 00:05:49.331
So demand for services like

00:05:49.332 --> 00:05:51.029
travel, entertainment -- all

00:05:51.039 --> 00:05:53.189
fell through the floor -- and so the

00:05:53.199 --> 00:05:54.710
federal government's reaction to that

00:05:54.720 --> 00:05:57.270
was to be concerned about deflation.

00:05:57.280 --> 00:06:00.128
To fight that, they expanded the money supply,

00:06:00.129 --> 00:06:01.355
because by printing money,

00:06:01.356 --> 00:06:03.400
that reduces the interest rate, then it becomes

00:06:03.401 --> 00:06:05.005
less attractive to save your money

00:06:05.006 --> 00:06:06.756
and get a tiny bit of interest, and it becomes

00:06:06.757 --> 00:06:08.784
more attractive to spend your money.

00:06:09.267 --> 00:06:10.194
Here in green is the

00:06:10.195 --> 00:06:13.110
MZM money supply -- MZM stands for

00:06:13.120 --> 00:06:14.727
"money zero maturity"

00:06:14.728 --> 00:06:16.807
and what that consists of is the

00:06:16.808 --> 00:06:19.590
M1 supply -- which is coins, currency,

00:06:19.600 --> 00:06:21.990
and checking accounts -- and it combines

00:06:22.000 --> 00:06:23.909
that with savings accounts and

00:06:23.919 --> 00:06:25.510
money market accounts, which many people

00:06:25.520 --> 00:06:26.848
use as an alternate form of a

00:06:26.849 --> 00:06:28.309
savings account these days.

00:06:28.319 --> 00:06:30.444
I've normalized that number to the gross

00:06:30.445 --> 00:06:32.150
domestic product -- that is the value of

00:06:32.160 --> 00:06:33.670
all goods and services produced in the

00:06:33.680 --> 00:06:35.270
U.S. in one year.

00:06:35.280 --> 00:06:38.390
The money supply as a fraction of the

00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:39.990
productive output of the U.S.

00:06:40.000 --> 00:06:41.859
has been going up for the last forty years,

00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:43.672
and you can see here at 2020

00:06:43.673 --> 00:06:45.189
the line spikes up from

00:06:45.199 --> 00:06:48.150
about 70 percent to over 100 percent.

00:06:48.160 --> 00:06:50.324
The word "unprecedented" gets thrown around a lot

00:06:50.325 --> 00:06:52.356
for this crisis, but truly, if you look at

00:06:52.357 --> 00:06:53.895
long-term plots like this and you see

00:06:53.896 --> 00:06:55.510
the size and the slope

00:06:55.520 --> 00:06:57.270
of this money printing that's been

00:06:57.280 --> 00:06:58.629
happening in the last several months --

00:06:58.639 --> 00:07:00.482
it's truly breathtaking.

00:07:00.677 --> 00:07:02.192
Of course the government can

00:07:02.193 --> 00:07:04.706
print as much or as little money as it wants,

00:07:04.707 --> 00:07:06.070
with nothing stopping them from

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:07.510
doing whatever they want --

00:07:07.520 --> 00:07:10.182
this has been true since [President] Nixon abolished

00:07:10.183 --> 00:07:12.844
the linkage of the U.S. dollar to gold.

00:07:13.088 --> 00:07:14.550
Looking at the bottom line here,

00:07:14.560 --> 00:07:16.230
this is how much money is the U.S.

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:17.350
government taking in

00:07:17.360 --> 00:07:18.950
minus how much money is the U.S.

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:20.870
government spending, on a monthly basis.

00:07:20.880 --> 00:07:23.350
So, it's basically taxes minus spending.

00:07:23.360 --> 00:07:25.110
It spikes four times a year because

00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:26.790
that's when estimated taxes are due

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:29.222
and so there's that seasonal structure to it.

00:07:29.496 --> 00:07:31.266
As you can see it really tanked,

00:07:31.267 --> 00:07:33.918
in especially quarter 2 of 2020.

00:07:33.919 --> 00:07:35.990
April 15, which is the normal deadline

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.830
for taxes to be due, got pushed back to

00:07:37.840 --> 00:07:39.749
July 15, due to the pandemic.

00:07:39.759 --> 00:07:41.749
So there was no tax revenue coming in,

00:07:41.759 --> 00:07:43.689
yet the government was continuing to spend

00:07:43.690 --> 00:07:45.150
money as it was before.

00:07:45.151 --> 00:07:46.309
The spending didn't stop,

00:07:46.338 --> 00:07:48.161
just the income stopped.

00:07:48.395 --> 00:07:50.390
And so this might reverse itself,

00:07:50.400 --> 00:07:52.564
now that July 15 has come and gone,

00:07:52.565 --> 00:07:55.612
with a correspondingly high spike in taxes --

00:07:55.613 --> 00:07:58.709
that is assuming that this July 15 was a bonanza

00:07:58.710 --> 00:08:00.090
from the point of view of the IRS

00:08:00.091 --> 00:08:01.282
with a whole lot of tax money coming in --

00:08:01.283 --> 00:08:03.129
we'll see if that was actually the case.

00:08:03.280 --> 00:08:05.400
If you integrate this over time,

00:08:05.401 --> 00:08:07.139
then you get the black line

00:08:07.140 --> 00:08:08.710
that's on top, which is the

00:08:08.720 --> 00:08:11.699
total federal debt normalized to GDP, again.

00:08:11.976 --> 00:08:13.930
In the aftermath of the

00:08:13.931 --> 00:08:16.824
2008-2009 financial crisis,

00:08:16.825 --> 00:08:18.373
the government was spending

00:08:18.374 --> 00:08:19.507
quite a bit more money

00:08:19.508 --> 00:08:20.675
than it was collecting,

00:08:20.676 --> 00:08:22.897
and as a result, when you time integrate that,

00:08:22.898 --> 00:08:24.177
you get the black line up here

00:08:24.178 --> 00:08:26.473
in the federal debt to GDP.

00:08:26.781 --> 00:08:28.769
And now we're at this point here

00:08:28.770 --> 00:08:30.151
at the beginning of the year --

00:08:30.152 --> 00:08:32.958
the debt to GDP ratio is about 110 percent

00:08:32.959 --> 00:08:35.689
and that is before the pandemic.

00:08:36.719 --> 00:08:38.790
In the G20, there are eight countries

00:08:38.800 --> 00:08:40.230
that have been reporting

00:08:40.240 --> 00:08:42.389
statistics on the amount of money that's

00:08:42.399 --> 00:08:45.014
in circulation in their particular currency.

00:08:45.117 --> 00:08:47.269
Here, I've normalized the amount of money

00:08:47.279 --> 00:08:48.470
in every country to be

00:08:48.480 --> 00:08:51.670
equal to 1 on January of 2020.

00:08:51.680 --> 00:08:53.670
There's this hockey stick shape to this

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:56.710
curve of how much money is circulating.

00:08:56.720 --> 00:08:59.479
In the United States, the M1 expansion has been

00:08:59.480 --> 00:09:02.239
to the tune of about 1.33 trillion dollars --

00:09:02.240 --> 00:09:03.642
which amounts to a

00:09:03.643 --> 00:09:04.962
increase in the money supply of about

00:09:04.963 --> 00:09:07.269
300 million dollars per hour.

00:09:07.279 --> 00:09:09.110
Now, if you compare this to, for example,

00:09:09.120 --> 00:09:10.870
the market cap of Monero -- that's

00:09:10.880 --> 00:09:13.276
something on the order of one and a half billion --

00:09:13.277 --> 00:09:15.269
so the money supply of the U.S.

00:09:15.279 --> 00:09:19.039
expanded by the size of Monero's market cap,

00:09:19.040 --> 00:09:20.852
roughly five times every day

00:09:20.853 --> 00:09:23.181
for the last six months.

00:09:23.839 --> 00:09:26.310
Let's broaden our focus to not just the

00:09:26.320 --> 00:09:28.639
eight countries in the G20 that have reported

00:09:28.640 --> 00:09:30.389
results recently, but let's look at

00:09:30.399 --> 00:09:32.070
all the G20 fiat currencies

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:34.550
and let's also expand the time frame

00:09:34.561 --> 00:09:36.709
in which we're looking back to 2009,

00:09:36.710 --> 00:09:39.039
the year in which Bitcoin came out.

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:41.350
Every country's money is equal to 1

00:09:41.360 --> 00:09:42.949
at the beginning of 2009.

00:09:42.959 --> 00:09:44.790
You can see that there's not one of the

00:09:44.800 --> 00:09:47.110
G20 currencies that has been flat

00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:48.832
or has actually decreased their

00:09:48.833 --> 00:09:49.870
money supply over time --

00:09:49.871 --> 00:09:51.849
it's all increased.

